 The Football Association has been fined £25,630 (30,000 euros) by UEFA for the behaviour of England fans during the Euro 2020 semi-final win over Denmark, which included a laser pointer being shone at Denmark goalkeeper Kasper Schmeichel. The punishment, confirmed on Saturday by the European governing body, also takes into account disturbances during the national anthems at Wembley and the setting off of fireworks inside the stadium, reports Sky Sports. The FA was charged with the three offences after the game and the sanctions were imposed following consideration by UEFA’s control, ethics and disciplinary body.   UEFA has charged England after a laser pointer was directed at Denmark keeper Kasper Schmeichel during Wednesday's Euro 2020 semi-final at Wembley. Television pictures showed a green light on Schmeichel's face just before Harry Kane took an extra-time penalty, reports the BBC. Schmeichel saved the spot-kick but Kane scored… July 8, 2021 In "Sports" ...as Danish FA says Eriksen awake and waiting more tests in hospital Christian Eriksen, a Danish midfielder, passed out as the ball was thrown to him during his team’s Euro 2020 match against Finland on Saturday prompting his team mates to call for medical attention for which he was given… June 12, 2021 In "Top Stories" Denmark midfielder Christian Eriksen is stable in hospital after collapsing during his country's opening Euro 2020 game against Finland in Copenhagen.   The Inter star went down during the opening half of the Group B match and required extensive medical attention on the pitch before he was removed on a… June 13, 2021 In "Sports"